no-redundant-in-check

Flags `"y" in x` checks where the type of x already has y as a required
(non-optional) property in all union constituents. The check is dead code
because the property is guaranteed to exist at runtime.

Source: custom rule for lintcn

The Problem

  interface User { name: string; age: number }
  function process(user: User) {
    if ('name' in user) {  // redundant — User always has 'name'
      console.log(user.name)
    }
  }

The `in` operator returns true if the named property exists on the object.
When the type system already guarantees the property is present and non-optional,
the check can never be false. This is dead code that adds noise and confuses
readers about the type's guarantees.

What Gets Flagged

  Situation                           Flagged   Reason
  Required property on interface      yes       always present
  Required in ALL union members        yes       always present in every variant
  Required on class                    yes       always present
  Required from base interface         yes       inherited, always present

What Is NOT Flagged

  Situation                           Reason
  Optional property (?)               key may not exist at runtime
  Property in some union members       valid discriminated union narrowing
  any / unknown / type parameter       can't reason statically
  Index signature (Record<string, T>) property may not exist
  Computed key (variable)              can't determine property name
  Null / undefined in union            in check helps narrow away nullish
